{
  "doc_id": "42440",
  "text": "Narcolepsy is a neurologic disease characterized by the extensive loss of Hcrt neurons without degeneration of neighboring cells (Kilduff and Peyron, 2000; [CITATION_1] . Narcoleptic patients are unable to sustain long periods of consolidated wakefulness and must nap frequently; some patients also experience attacks of cataplexy which greatly affects their quality of life (Kornum et al., 2017) . However, total sleep time in untreated narcoleptic patients as well as in mouse models of narcolepsy does not differ from controls over the 24-h period [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , a phenotype that is distinct from the lethargy observed after LH lesions or acute LH neuronal inhibition. Chemogenetic excitation of Hcrt neurons in mice [CITATION_5] ) produced a 30% increase in wake time during the first hour of stimulation compared to controls but no significant difference was observed after the second hour, which also differs from the effects of LH excitation cited above. Thus, Hcrt neuron stimulation and ablation studies do not fully recapitulate the effects on wake and sleep observed after manipulations of LH neuron activity, indicating that there are likely other wake-promoting neuronal populations in the LH that may be involved in sleep/wake regulation.",
